			</section>

			<!-- Sleep -->
			<section>
				<h2>Sleep optimization</h2>
				<p>Sleep is the highest-leverage health behavior. I track it obsessively with two devices and have made several environmental interventions.</p>

				<h3>Devices</h3>
				<ul>
					<li><strong>Eight Sleep Pod 5</strong> &mdash; bed temperature control, sleep scoring, HRV, respiratory rate, snoring detection, sleep stages</li>
					<li><strong>Whoop MG</strong> &mdash; recovery score, strain, HRV, RHR, SPO2, sleep performance</li>
				</ul>

				<h3>Environmental interventions</h3>
				<ul>
					<li><strong>Hamvay-Lang PureDelight 800fp winter duvet</strong> ($885) &mdash; Bayesian analysis showed bed temperature has a +3.0 score/&deg;C causal effect on Eight Sleep sleep score. The duvet raises bed temperature, improving sleep quality. Estimated 165-day payback period.</li>
					<li><strong>Bed incline</strong> &mdash; Eight Sleep adjustable base, slight incline for reflux and breathing</li>
					<li><strong>Nasal strips + Nasacort</strong> &mdash; first night with this combination: zero snoring (vs. 13.2 min/night average). The clearest win in the protocol.</li>
				</ul>

				<h3>Medications</h3>
				<ul>
					<li><strong>Trazodone 50mg</strong> &mdash; sleep maintenance. Whoop data confirms it wears off at 4-5 hours, leading to second-half fragmentation.</li>
					<li><strong>Melatonin 300mcg</strong> &mdash; low-dose for sleep onset. Higher doses are not more effective.</li>
				</ul>

				<h3>Key findings</h3>
				<ul>
					<li>Sleep duration is the #1 lever: +8.6 Whoop recovery points per hour</li>
					<li>Bedtime before 11pm yields a 13-point recovery advantage</li>
					<li>SPO2 drops below 95% on 36% of nights (flagged for apnea investigation)</li>
					<li>Disturbances trending up (+0.009/day, p&lt;0.0001)</li>
				</ul>
			</section>

			<!-- Tracking -->
			<section>
				<h2>Tracking</h2>
				<p>I maintain a SQLite database of nightly health data with 12+ tables, synced from Eight Sleep and Whoop APIs. Metrics that actually influence decisions:</p>
				<ul>
					<li><strong>Sleep score</strong> (Eight Sleep) &mdash; primary outcome for environmental experiments</li>
					<li><strong>Recovery</strong> (Whoop) &mdash; composite of HRV, RHR, sleep quality; guides training intensity</li>
					<li><strong>HRV</strong> &mdash; parasympathetic tone; trending metric for stress and recovery</li>
					<li><strong>Snoring duration</strong> (Eight Sleep) &mdash; proxy for airway obstruction; guides nasal interventions</li>
					<li><strong>SPO2</strong> (Whoop) &mdash; blood oxygen; apnea screening metric</li>
				</ul>
				<p>Most other metrics (strain, respiratory rate, sleep stages) I log but rarely act on directly.</p>
			</section>

			<!-- Investigating -->
			<section>
				<h2>What I'm investigating</h2>
				<ul>
					<li><strong>Sleep apnea</strong> &mdash; Bayesian estimate: 66% probability based on SPO2 patterns, snoring, and family history. Pending home sleep study. Treatment options: CPAP, Inspire nerve stimulator, Dayvigo (lemborexant).</li>
					<li><strong>Rapamycin</strong> &mdash; strongest longevity candidate in the Rx list (ITP mice +26% lifespan). Requires physician willing to prescribe off-label. Immunosuppression concern.</li>
					<li><strong>Semaglutide</strong> &mdash; SELECT trial HR 0.80 for MACE. High cost ($6K/yr) but enormous effect size. Watching for generic timeline.</li>
					<li><strong>Lion's mane, cistanche</strong> &mdash; recently added to stack. Low evidence confidence but low cost.</li>
					<li><strong>Trazodone alternatives</strong> &mdash; wears off at 4-5h. Evaluating lemborexant (Dayvigo) for better second-half sleep maintenance.</li>
				</ul>
			</section>

			<!-- Methodology -->
			<section>
				<h2>Methodology</h2>
				<p>This page is generated from the <a href="https://github.com/maxghenis/optiqal-ai">Optiqal</a> Python package. The data pipeline:</p>
				<ol>
					<li>Literature hazard ratios are entered into a structured catalog with uncertainty estimates, study-quality tiers, and confounding priors</li>
					<li>Each HR is shrunk toward null by a <strong>tiered</strong> publication-bias correction: 10% for preregistered RCTs with hard endpoints, 20&ndash;30% for standard RCTs and cohorts, 50% for supplement-industry RCTs, 70% for animal-only evidence</li>
					<li>A Beta-distributed confounding prior discounts the causal fraction (e.g., Beta(2.5, 4) means ~38% of the observed effect is believed causal for medical interventions, calibrated against observed RCT-vs-observational gaps)</li>
					<li>{config.n_simulations.toLocaleString()} Monte Carlo simulations propagate uncertainty through CDC life tables for a {profile.age}-year-old {profile.sex}. The resulting <strong>posterior hazard ratio</strong> (what the simulator actually applies) is reported alongside the literature HR so readers can see the shrinkage that matters</li>
					<li>Mechanism clusters (anti-inflammatory polyphenols, NAD+ precursors, antioxidants, mitochondrial-support, senolytics, neurotrophics, methylation-donors) apply within-cluster diminishing-returns schedules so correlated supplements don't stack additively</li>
					<li>Expected days gained = mean QALY gain &times; 365.25</li>
					<li>Greedy portfolio optimizer selects items by marginal net value; a portfolio-level QALY ceiling ({summary.portfolio_qaly_ceiling ?? 3.0}) applies a concave saturation to the additive total, bounded by primary-prevention CEA literature</li>
					<li>Bundled products carry an allocated per-ingredient cost share so bundled items contribute to $/QALY accounting</li>
				</ol>
				<p>Evidence confidence labels: <span class="evidence-badge evidence-high">high</span> = strong causal prior + tight uncertainty; <span class="evidence-badge evidence-medium">medium</span> = moderate evidence or wider uncertainty; <span class="evidence-badge evidence-low">low</span> = weak causal evidence, speculative.</p>
				<p>Profile: {profile.age}yo {profile.sex}, BMI {profile.bmi_category}, {profile.smoking_status} smoker. WTP ${config.wtp.toLocaleString()}/QALY, {config.horizon_years}-year horizon, {pct(config.qaly_discount_rate)} QALY discount, {pct(config.cost_discount_rate)} cost discount, {config.n_simulations.toLocaleString()} simulations. Saturated QALY total: {summary.total_qaly} (raw additive: {summary.total_raw_qaly}). Ground-up audit total: {groundUpSummary.total_stack_qaly} QALY ({groundUpSummary.total_stack_days} days).</p>
			</section>
